cism, and theatrical spectacle even while enjoying the prestige that came from rejecting them. By focusing on moments when reigning aesthetic oppositions and hierarchies threatened to collapse, this study offers a powerful model for recovering shades of grey in the traditionally black-and-white historiographies of twentieth-century music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aModernism (Music)xHistoryy20th century. 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aestheticsy20th century. 0aMusicy20th centuryxPhilosophy and esthetics. 0aOperay20th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520970700?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520970700zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520970700/original  a978-3-11-066767-7 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA